05974nam a2200793Ia 9781501720130DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017201307 a10.7591/97815017201302doi  a(DE-B1597)496378  a(OCoLC)1012640744  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0230002bisacsh04a323/.04209592231 aRodan, Garry, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aParticipation without Democracy :bContaining Conflict in Southeast Asia /cGarry Rodan. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (300 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations and Acronyms -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: STRUGGLES OVER POLITICAL REPRESENTATION -- t1. THEORIZING INSTITUTIONS OF POLITICAL PARTICIPATION AND REPRESENTATION -- t2. IDEOLOGIES OF POLITICAL REPRESENTATION AND THE MODE OF PARTICIPATION FRAMEWORK -- t3. HISTORY, CAPITALISM, AND CONFLICT -- t4. NOMINATED MEMBERS OF PARLIAMENT IN SINGAPORE -- t5. PUBLIC FEEDBACK IN SINGAPORE’S CONSULTATIVE AUTHORITARIANISM -- t6. THE PHILIPPINES’ PARTY-LIST SYSTEM, REFORMERS, AND OLIGARCHS -- t7. PARTICIPATORY BUDGETING IN THE PHILIPPINES -- t8. MALAYSIA’S FAILED CONSULTATIVE REPRESENTATION EXPERIMENTS -- t9. CIVIL SOCIETY AND ELECTORAL REFORM IN MALAYSIA -- tConclusion: CAPITALISM, INSTITUTIONS, AND IDEOLOGY -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the past quarter century new ideologies of participation and representation have proliferated across democratic and non-democratic regimes. In Participation without Democracy, Garry Rodan breaks new conceptual ground in examining the social forces that underpin the emergence of these innovations in Southeast Asia. Rodan explains that there is, however, a central paradox in this recalibration of politics: expanded political participation is serving to constrain contestation more than to enhance it.Participation without Democracy uses Rodan’s long-term fieldwork in Singapore, the Philippines, and Malaysia to develop a modes of participation (MOP) framework that has general application across different regime types among both early-developing and late-developing capitalist societies. His MOP framework is a sophisticated, original, and universally relevant way of analyzing this phenomenon. Rodan uses MOP and his case studies to highlight important differences among social and political forces over the roles and forms of collective organization in political representation. In addition, he identifies and distinguishes hitherto neglected non-democratic ideologies of representation and their influence within both democratic and authoritarian regimes. Participation without Democracy suggests that to address the new politics that both provokes these institutional experiments and is affected by them we need to know who can participate, how, and on what issues, and we need to take the non-democratic institutions and ideologies as seriously as the democratic ones.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aDemocracyzSoutheast AsiavCase studies. 0aPolitical participationzSoutheast AsiavCase studies. 0aRepresentative government and representationzSoutheast AsiavCase studies. 0aSocial conflictzSoutheast AsiavCase studies. 4aAsian Studies. 4aGeneral Economics. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh  ademocratization, authoritarianism, capitalism, political representation, inequality.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyt